highlights.description: Pretty amazing. The bedroom, the library books and reading as central to who Jackie is.
A very unusual town! A model for talking across divides?
Violence and gender discrimination shaped Ananda's childhood.
Her daughter is becoming apathetic about the guns problem. Who's going to listen?
Why Jackie sent her kids to private school, which she now views as a mistake.
Police using their power to intimidate her niece into talking about a dude she knows.
Madison's "play acting" progressivism.

How privileged white people feed off the racial divide, to get "that glow" they crave. And what it did  to Jackie's kids to be in a white school where they were "turned into white kids in their brains."
Another take on "the glow" the white people get from living in Madison
The disconnects of Madison. And so many have no idea.
Some people are having a war inside themselves about how much they want to know.
The night the SWAT team appeared at her home.
Her fear her daughter would come home and see this. And her own memories about the violence of her childhood.
Interesting comment. New arrivals to the US don't understand how racism works here.
The "savior complex" of some white people.
It's not about misunderstanding. It's about people not caring enough to understand, as in: "I like animals and you care about racism."
There's often only space for one leader of color.
It's fashionable now to put leaders of color on a pedestal. They are "godifyed".
"There is no space for us to be human."
Recent experience of meeting a Republican, during the week of the Kavanaugh hearing and an ICE raid in Madison. Her first reaction on learning he was a Republican: shutting down, disengaging.
Fascinating point about the sacredness of stories, and how they can be exploited.
I don't understand myself in the context of this community. The few "menu options" that you have available for me don't match.
Ananda: Every attempt to disrupt (how it works now in Madison) is valuable.

Concerns about high school lock-downs and metal detectors and our ability to have a conversation about this difficult issue. Should be prefaced by playing "Ananda introduction" from this conversation.

Woman speaking about tension she feels enjoying the offerings of Madison while knowing many people here do not have the same access; Should be prefaced by playing "Colleen introduction" from this conversation.
Experience of trying to convey concerns over ICE roundups to a new acquaintance introduced as a Republican; should be prefaced by playing "Colleen introduction" from this conversation.

This is a story from Tony, speaking from first hand experience about her changing perception of Madison after getting to know more low income people in the area. Introductory remarks made at 7:54, grew up in a small, diverse, town in upstate New York

This is a story from Ananda, speaking from first hand experience about her daughter going to a school with metal detectors. It left her feeling confused and discouraged.  Introductory remarks made at 9:35, from Brazil, grew up working class in a very violent neighborhood, oldest of three siblings, experienced sexism within the home growing up, not allowed to go to good schools like her brothers.

This is a story from Nancy, speaking from first hand experience about raising her kids in a community that felt very safe for her. Her kids could behave badly but she realizes not all kids could misbehave and get away with it. Introductory remarks for Nancy at 5:47 oldest of 5 kids, took care of them a lot.
